:"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"6555"},{"type":"tags","id":"6556"},{"type":"tags","id":"6571"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14168/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14168/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"34366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"53223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"54762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"54763"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14168/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14168/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"122312","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/122312"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset of severe chest pain radiating through to his back. He describes the pain as tearing in nature. He feels nauseated and is fearful for his health. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg in the right arm and 70/50 mmHg in the left arm, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Heart sounds are normal with no murmurs. Chest is clear to auscultation. There are no focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn electrocardiogram shows sinus tachycardia with no ischaemic changes. A chest X-ray demonstrates a widened mediastinum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Considering the most likely diagnosis, which one of the following most accurately approximates the one-year mortality rate if left untreated?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["10%","20%","50%","70%","90%"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of type A aortic dissection: sudden onset severe tearing chest pain radiating to the back, haemodynamic instability, differential blood pressure between arms (\u003E20 mmHg difference), and widened mediastinum on chest X-ray. The absence of ischaemic changes on electrocardiogram helps distinguish this from acute myocardial infarction, though both can present with severe chest pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E90%\u003C/strong\u003E is the most accurate approximation of the one-year mortality rate for untreated type A aortic dissection. Without surgical intervention, mortality is extremely high, with most deaths occurring within the first few days to weeks due to rupture, cardiac tamponade, or end-organ ischaemia. Historical data show that up to 90% of patients die within one year if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E10%\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E20%\u003C/strong\u003E significantly underestimate the lethality of untreated type A aortic dissection. Mortality approaches 50% within the first 48 hours and continues to rise rapidly thereafter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E50%\u003C/strong\u003E is closer to the short-term mortality (within days to weeks), but does not reflect the cumulative risk over one year, which is much higher.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E70%\u003C/strong\u003E still underestimates the true one-year mortality, as the vast majority of patients will not survive beyond a few months without intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType A aortic dissection is a surgical emergency requiring immediate cardiothoracic surgical consultation. The differential blood pressure between arms, widened mediastinum, and characteristic pain pattern are key diagnostic features that should prompt urgent imaging with computed tomography angiography or transoesophageal echocardiography to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Untreated type A aortic dissection carries an extremely high mortality rate, with up to 90% of patients dying within one year.","Immediate surgical intervention is the standard of care for type A aortic dissection and significantly improves survival."],"references":["Harky A, Singh VP, Khan D, Sajid MM, Kermali M, Othman A. Factors Affecting Outcomes in Acute Type A Aortic Dissection: A Systematic Review. Heart Lung Circ. 2020;29(11):1668-1681. doi:10.1016/j.hlc.2020.05.113","Afifi RO, Sandhu HK, Leake SS, et al. Determinants of Operative Mortality in Patients With Ruptured Acute Type A Aortic Dissection. Ann Thorac Surg. 2016;101(1):64-71. doi:10.1016/j.athoracsur.2015.07.007","Teurneau-Hermansson K, Ede J, Larsson M, et al. Mortality after non-surgically treated acute type A aortic  dissection is higher than previously reported. Eur J Cardiothorac Surg. 2024 Feb 3; 65(2):ezae039."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"103725"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/122312/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/122312/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21295"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/122312/question","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/122312/relationships/question"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/122312/stemMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/122312/relationships/stemMedia"}},"explanationMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/122312/explanationMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/122312/relationships/explanationMedia"}}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"103725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/103725"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-10-24T13:08:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-10-24T13:28:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14168"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/103725/item","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/103725/relationships/item"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"122312"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/103725/content","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/103725/relationships/content"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/group","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/relationships/group"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/heading","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/relationships/heading"}},"ancestors":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/ancestors","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/relationships/ancestors"}},"parents":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/parents","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/relationships/parents"}},"children":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/children","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/relationships/children"}},"descendants":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/descendants","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/relationships/descendants"}},"curricula":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/curricula","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2/relationships/curricula"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co